 z quality of loot, or there's no exchange.  all comparison either considers them as exchangable, or there is no comparison.  as an example, if xp is not exchangable with loot, then the equality of aquiring xp does not have any bearing on equility to the distribution of loot, and there should be two distinct, seperate, and as well independent distribution measure for each; on the other hand, if they are exchangable, then equaility cannot be measured purely by xp, because loots do have value just as xp.  no drop items is a prime example of non-exchangables.<br>
<br>
now nbg is so difficult to defend when you are in a pick up group. easily, the free exchange/trade between all people require all having the same oppertunity, or there'd be previlaged class(es).  though, previlaging a class of people does not mean it is necessarily unfair, the notion of a &quot;just&quot; distribution is still a debatable subject.  however, let me, out of popular opinion, assume that the just method of distributing xp/loot(thereon meaning any object loot and cash) is such that they are divided equally between 2 people if the 2 people spend the equal amount of time at the same place grouping with each other.  nbg must be unfair under the above mentioned notion of just distribution since nbg necessarily reward one person with higher value of exchangables than the other person provided the two person have different &quot;needs&quot; (in regards to &quot;need&quot; before greed).<br>
<br>
of course, let's not forget that some classes' jobs are actually more risky than others, some are functionally more popular than others, and etc.  and as well, eq penalizes some classes/races accordingly to try to offset the imbalance which makes it all the messier.<br>
<br>
anyway, if time is the only variable considered, then nbg is unfair, period.  well, the funny thing is that it is not necessary not benifical, especially to a group of friends, or guild.  nbg inside a guild, for example, would excempt the guild's economic situation from the outside economic influences (your guild's economy is independent from the ec one, simply put).  in this case, the benifit is that your guild's internal economy would be less likely be influence by outside instability, inflation and etc.  it's, for example, a silly thing to think that a business would openly let different photocopy shop from everywhere in the world to bid on copying its document than to let its own photocopy department to do it and still expect efficiency within the business.  and the demise of photocopying shops world wide would not have as much of an influence to the photo copying department within the business as if it were actually an independent firm.<br>
<br>
and i don't see any point of talking honour here, either you honour your contract or you don't, and that only regard exchange/trade, which i think was not even a slight problem here.  greed/dishonour that ppl talk about here, as i understand it, is nothing but a disbute on the definition of &quot;just distribution.&quot;  as well, need/honour is nothing but an agreement on the definition.  after all, what is exchangable, will be exchanged one time or the other for a certain value, regardless of its immediacy.<br>
<br>
hopefully i made sense, feel free to correct me if i were wrong. <p><center><A HREF="http://home.earthlink.net/~roseydawn" TARGET="_top">
